07463nam a22014295i 9780691183992DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911839927 a10.1515/97806911839922doi  a(DE-B1597)501678  a(OCoLC)1056070137  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHN385 7aBUS0690002bisacsh04a330.12609412231 aBoyer, George R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Winding Road to the Welfare State :bEconomic Insecurity and Social Welfare Policy in Britain /cGeorge R. Boyer, George R. Boyer. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Princeton Economic History of the Western World ;v9100tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Economic Insecurity and Social Policy -- tPART I. Social Policy and Self- Help in Victorian Britain -- t2. Poor Relief, Charity, and Self- Help in Crisis Times, 1834-69 -- t3. Social Welfare Policy, Living Standards, and Self- Help, 1861-1908 -- t4. Unemployment and Unemployment Relief -- t5. Old Age Poverty and Pauperism -- tPART II. Constructing the Welfare State -- t6. Living Standards in Edwardian England and the Liberal Welfare Reforms -- t7. Social Welfare Policy and Living Standards between the Wars -- t8. The Beveridge Report and the Implementation of the Welfare State -- t9. What Was Gained -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow did Britain transform itself from a nation of workhouses to one that became a model for the modern welfare state? The Winding Road to the Welfare State investigates the evolution of living standards and welfare policies in Britain from the 1830s to 1950 and provides insights into how British working-class households coped with economic insecurity. George Boyer examines the retrenchment in Victorian poor relief, the Liberal Welfare Reforms, and the beginnings of the postwar welfare state, and he describes how workers altered spending and saving methods based on changing government policies.From the cutting back of the Poor Law after 1834 to Parliament's abrupt about-face in 1906 with the adoption of the Liberal Welfare Reforms, Boyer offers new explanations for oscillations in Britain's social policies and how these shaped worker well-being. The Poor Law's increasing stinginess led skilled manual workers to adopt self-help strategies, but this was not a feasible option for low-skilled workers, many of whom continued to rely on the Poor Law into old age. In contrast, the Liberal Welfare Reforms were a major watershed, marking the end of seven decades of declining support for the needy. Concluding with the Beveridge Report and Labor's social policies in the late 1940s, Boyer shows how the Liberal Welfare Reforms laid the foundations for a national social safety net.A sweeping look at economic pressures after the Industrial Revolution, The Winding Road to the Welfare State illustrates how British welfare policy waxed and waned over the course of a century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPublic welfarezGreat BritainxHistory. 0aWelfare statezGreat BritainxHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  a1905 Unemployed Workmen Act.  aBeveridge Report.  aBritish social policy.  aBritish social welfare policy.  aBritish welfare policy.  aCrusade Against Outrelief.  aLiberal Welfare Reforms.  aNational Health Service.  aPoor Law.  aVictorian poor relief.  acharity.  aeconomic dislocations.  aeconomic insecurity.  aeconomic loss.  afamily support.  afinancial distress.  afriendly societies.  aincome loss.  aindust